SIMPLE: proboscis
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proboscis
<hw>Pro*bos"cis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Proboscides</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. fr. Gr. <?/; <?/
before + <?/ to feed, graze.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>A hollow organ or tube attached to the head, or connected with the
mouth, of various animals, and generally used in taking food or drink; a
snout; a trunk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The proboscis of an elephant is a flexible muscular
elongation of the nose. The proboscis of insects is usually a chitinous
tube formed by the modified maxill⟦ae⟧, or by the labium. See
<xex>Illusts</xex>. of <er>Hemiptera</er> and
<er>Lepidoptera</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>By extension, applied to various
tubelike mouth organs of the lower animals that can be everted or
protruded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The proboscis of annelids and of mollusks is usually a
portion of the pharynx that can be everted or protruded. That of
nemerteans is a special long internal organ, not connected with the
mouth, and not used in feeding, but capable of being protruded from a
pore in the head. See <xex>Illust.</xex> in Appendix.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The nose.</def> <mark>[Jocose]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Proboscis monkey</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Kahau</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Procacious</ent>⟦br⟧
